Breeding pigeons is a common place hobby amongst New Yorkers. Both young and old utilize the roofs and housetops for the purpose. The one shown is at Catherine near Cherry Streets.
March 6, 1934.

title: Cherry Street - Catherine Street looking east

text:
Catherine Street, north from and including Cherry Street. The view shows Knickerbocker Village in the process of construction.

March 6, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)

Cherry Street, south side, east from Catherine, to, but not including Market Slips. Also shown is Catherine Slip, east side, south from and including Cherry, to and including Water Streets. A portion of the excavation for Knickerbocker Village appears in the foreground, with the Manhattan Bridge towering overhead.
March 6, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

The same, a further view eastward.
March 6, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)

Similar to No. 2, showing mainly Nos. 143 to 159. The arched roof building at the S.W. corner of Market Slip bears No. 83 on
that and 159 on Cherry Street.
1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
